{"title_page": "Nikolai Kardashev", "text_new": "'''Nikolai Semenovich Kardashev<ref>Also [[Romanization of Russian|transliterated]] '''Kardashov''', preserving the letter ''[[Yo (Cyrillic)#Russian|yo]]''.</ref>''' ({{lang-rus|\u041d\u0438\u043a\u043e\u043b\u0430\u0301\u0439 \u0421\u0435\u043c\u0451\u043d\u043e\u0432\u0438\u0447 \u041a\u0430\u0440\u0434\u0430\u0448\u0451\u0432|p=n\u02b2\u026ak\u0250\u02c8laj s\u02b2\u026a\u02c8m\u02b2\u0275n\u0259v\u02b2\u026at\u0255 k\u0259rd\u0250\u02c8\u0282of}}; 25 April 1932 \u2013 3 August 2019<ref>{{cite web|url=https://rossaprimavera.ru/news/79e0fc22|title=\u0423\u043c\u0435\u0440 \u0432\u044b\u0434\u0430\u044e\u0449\u0438\u0439\u0441\u044f \u0441\u043e\u0432\u0435\u0442\u0441\u043a\u0438\u0439 \u0430\u0441\u0442\u0440\u043e\u0444\u0438\u0437\u0438\u043a \u041d\u0438\u043a\u043e\u043b\u0430\u0439 \u041a\u0430\u0440\u0434\u0430\u0448\u0435\u0432|date=2019-08-04|publisher=\u041a\u0440\u0430\u0441\u043d\u0430\u044f \u0412\u0435\u0441\u043d\u0430|language=ru}}</ref>) was a [[Soviet Union|Soviet]] and [[Russia]]n astrophysicist, Doctor of Physical and Mathematical Sciences, and the deputy director of the [[Astro Space Center (Russia)|Astro Space Center]] of PN [[Lebedev Physical Institute]] of the [[Russian Academy of Sciences]] in Moscow.{{Infobox person\n| name               = Nikolai Kardashev\n| image              = Kardashev-e1458061627610.jpg\n| caption            = \n| birth_name         = Nikolai Semenovich Kardashev\n| birth_date         = {{birth date|1932|4|25}}\n| birth_place        = [[Moscow]], [[Russian SFSR]], [[Soviet Union]]\n| death_date         = {{death date and age|2019|8|3|1932|4|25}}\n| death_place        = [[Moscow]], [[Russia]]\n| nationality        = Soviet Union (Russia from 25 December 1991)\n| occupation         = Astrophysicist\n| years_active       = \n| known_for          = [[Kardashev scale]]\n| notable_works      = \n}}\n<br />\n\n==Early Life==\n\n# Born in Moscow to a family of professional revolutionaries involved with the [[Communist Party of the Soviet Union|Bolshevik Party]].<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://hkvalidate.perfdrive.com/captcha?ssa=6732a3b7-f249-4481-b2d8-b979db820c73&ssb=fm00f5e0iz1gph2ze3kkzd2f0&ssc=https%3A%2F%2Fiopscience.iop.org%2Farticle%2F10.3367%2FUFNe.0182.201206i.0677%2Fmeta&ssd=405741377509015&sse=cjkk@ipppcgdfng&ssf=6843b26fdf1a91859a96e59ec74c99f5cfca91f2&ssg=616b5581-078a-470a-bd7d-0c7892ae5f9d&ssh=854e7e18-5f8a-4d34-955d-27bfba365d36&ssi=8ffccafc-8427-4682-a17d-d4ac732b294f&ssj=1903d63e-48a1-4cfc-a1a2-11752a5ec723&ssk=support@shieldsquare.com&ssl=155695867491&ssm=66836733651201974102419827231121&ssn=f386fe603ac05bc65b29d6a87b074a7996ad3c2b963f-79a2-49b6-881526&sso=bfa048d1-7f444f767003d388ef5f4d6e23db539523922e70e080cf4c&ssp=39380969391588036462158802132976551&ssq=58015275559675528983755596932221824852874&ssr=MjA4LjgwLjE1My4yNA==&sss=Mozilla/4.0%20(Windows%20NT%205.1)%20AppleWebKit/535.7%20(KHTML,like%20zeco)%20Chrome/33.0.1750.154%20Safari/536.7&sst=ZoteroTranslationServer/WMF%20(mailto:services@lists.wikimedia.org)&ssu=Chrome/5.0%20(iPhone;%20U;%20CPU%20iPhone%20OS%203_0%20like%20Mac%20OS%20X;%20en-us)%20AppleWebKit/528.18%20(KHTML,%20like%20Gecko)%20Version/4.0%20Mobile/7A341%20Safari/528.16&ssv=m2qt1uuo1p1v941&ssw=&ssx=021940417581478&ssy=j@albdcjfakichhpjln@bknklonbiagpbfjeob@k&ssz=94ec63bb3fb088e|title=ShieldSquare Captcha|website=hkvalidate.perfdrive.com|doi=10.3367/ufne.0182.201206i.0677/meta|access-date=2020-04-28}}</ref>\n## Father's Name: Semen Karlovich Brike<ref name=\":0\" />\n## Mother's Name: Nina Nikolaevna Kardasheva<ref name=\":0\" />\n# His father was a prominent member of the party and his mother later joined as well before the 1917 October Revolution.<ref name=\":0\" />\n# In 1937 and 1938 (during [[Political repression in the Soviet Union|Stalin\u2019s repressions]]), both of his parents were arrested. His father was ultimately shot and his mother was forced into labor camps and would not be released for many years.<ref name=\":0\" />\n# Due to his parents\u2019 absence, he was sent to an orphanage where he then was taken by his mother\u2019s sister after a great deal of effort.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=https://asgardia.space/en/news/Astrophysics-Legend-Nikolai-Kardashev-Civilization-Ranking-Scale-Author-Died-Age-87|title=Astrophysics Legend Nikolai Kardashev, Civilization Ranking Scale Author, Died Age 87|website=asgardia.space|access-date=2020-04-28}}</ref>\n# His aunt then died during WWII when he was 16 years old and he then had to live on his own<ref name=\":1\" /> in a large communal flat.\n# His mother was released in 1956, at which point Nikolai had completed university.<ref name=\":0\" />\n# His interest in astronomy began while in 5th grade where he would attend a hobby group at the Moscow Planetarium.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n== Education ==\n\n# Moscow State. University (MGU in Russ. abbr.) - Astronomy division of the Mechanics and Mathematics Department<ref name=\":0\" />\n# Here he focus his studies/interests in radio astronomy. A field which was new and constantly developing.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n<br />\n\n== Career ==\n\n# Joined the Space Research Institute (IKI) of the USSR Academy of Sciences in 1967. <ref name=\":2\">{{Cite journal|last=I. Gurvits Leonid Joint Institute for VLBI ERIC|first=Dwingeloo|last2=Y. Kovalev Yuri Astro Space Center of Lebedev Physical Institute|first2=Moscow|last3=G. Edwards Philip CSIRO Astronomy and Space Science|first3=Marsfield|date=2019-12-16|title=Nikolai Kardashev|url=https://physicstoday.scitation.org/do/10.1063/PT.6.4o.20191216a/abs/|language=EN|doi=10.1063/PT.6.4o.20191216a}}</ref>\n# Became deputy director of IKI in 1977.<ref name=\":2\" />\n# During the dissolution of the USSR, Nikolai became the director of the Astro Space Center of the Lebedev Physical Institute.<ref name=\":2\" />\n# In 1978, Nikolai started a project called the Space VLBI mission RadioAstron. This mission covered more than 30 years and was finally launched in 2011.<ref name=\":2\" />\n## The RadioAstron mission has become one of the highlights of modern observational astrophysics.<ref name=\":2\" />\n\n== Organizations & His Role in Them<ref name=\":3\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.iau.org/administration/membership/individual/3990/|title=International Astronomical Union {{!}} IAU|website=www.iau.org|access-date=2020-04-28}}</ref><ref name=\":4\">{{Cite web|url=http://meti.org/en/blog/nikolai-kardashev-1932-2019|title=Nikolai Kardashev, 1932-2019 {{!}} METI International|website=meti.org|access-date=2020-04-28}}</ref><ref name=\":5\">{{Cite journal|last=I. Gurvits Leonid Joint Institute for VLBI ERIC|first=Dwingeloo|last2=Y. Kovalev Yuri Astro Space Center of Lebedev Physical Institute|first2=Moscow|last3=G. Edwards Philip CSIRO Astronomy and Space Science|first3=Marsfield|date=2019-12-16|title=Nikolai Kardashev|url=https://physicstoday.scitation.org/do/10.1063/PT.6.4o.20191216a/abs/|language=EN|doi=10.1063/PT.6.4o.20191216a}}</ref> ==\n\n# ''[[International Astronomical Union]]:<ref name=\":3\" />''\n## Vice-President of Executive Committee (1997-2003)<ref name=\":3\" />\n## Vice-President of Commission 51 Bio-Astronomy (1982-1991)<ref name=\":3\" />\n## Organizing Committee Member of Commission 40 Radio Astronomy (1967-1985)<ref name=\":3\" />\n## Member of Division B Facilities, Technologies and Data Science (2019)<ref name=\":3\" />\n## Member of Division F Planetary Systems and Astrobiology (2019)<ref name=\":3\" />\n## Member of Commission 40 Radio Astronomy (2015)<ref name=\":3\" />\n## Member of Commission 51 Bio-Astronomy (2015)<ref name=\":3\" />\n## Member of Division III Planetary Systems Sciences (2012)<ref name=\":3\" />\n## Member of Division X Radio Astronomy (2012)<ref name=\":3\" />\n## Member of Special Nominating Committee (2000-2003)<ref name=\":3\" />\n# ''[[Academy of Sciences of the Soviet Union|USSR Academy of Sciences]], Division of General Physics and Astronomy:''<ref name=\":4\" />\n## Corresponding (associate) member (December 12th 1976)<ref name=\":4\" />\n## Full Member (March 21st 1994)<ref name=\":4\" />\n## Served as chair of the Russian Academy of Sciences Council on Astronomy (1999-death)<ref name=\":4\" />\n# [[Committee on Space Research]]<ref name=\":5\" />\n## Vice President of the Committee for Space Research from 1982-1986.<ref name=\":5\" />\n\n== Scientific Career ==\n\n# Discoveries\n## Kardashev scale - 1964<ref name=\":5\" />\n## VLBI - Very Long Baseline Interferometry<ref name=\":5\" />\n### This replaced conventional radio transmission lines with magnetic tape recordings. Demonstrated in 1967<ref name=\":5\" />\n# Awards and Honors\n## 1988 - Shared the USSR's State Prize for the discovery of Radio Recombination Lines.<ref name=\":5\" />\n## In 2012, Nikolai received the Grote Reber Gold Medal for innovative lifetime contributions to radio astronomy.<ref name=\":5\" />\n# Published Works\n## 1963 - \"Candidate of Science\" dissertation, later promoted to higher level of doctoral thesis.<ref name=\":5\" />\n## 1964 - \u201cTransmission of Information by Extraterrestrial Civilizations\u201d<ref name=\":5\" />\n### Presented the classification of civilizations based on their level of power consumption spanning 20 orders of magnitude. Became known as Kardashev Scale.<ref name=\":5\" />\n\n== Film Career<ref name=\":6\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.imdb.com/name/nm9914444/|title=Nikolai Kardashev|website=IMDb|access-date=2020-04-28}}</ref> ==\n\n# His first connection with the film industry was in 1981. He was asked to be a consultant on the set of Petyla Oriona a Russian tv series documentary.<ref name=\":6\" />\n# Played himself in a tv show episode on the documentary series \"Spaces Deepest Secrets\" in 2018.<ref name=\":6\" />\n# Played himself in a tv show episode on the documentary series \"Horizon\" in 2018.<ref name=\":6\" />\n\n<br />\n\n== Extraterrestrial Research ==\n\n# May have predicted the existence of pulsars before they were officially discovered.<ref name=\":0\" />\n# \u2018Transmission of Information by Extraterrestrial Civilizations'<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n<br />\n\n== Death ==\n\n# Passed away on August 3rd 2019 at the age of 87.<ref name=\":1\" />\n\n==See also==\n* [[Kardashev scale]]\n* [[Astroengineering]]\n* [[Drake equation]]\n* [[SETI]]\n* [[Planetary civilization]]\n* [[Orders of magnitude (power)]]\n* [[Orders of magnitude (energy)]]\n* [[Technological singularity]]\n* [[World energy resources and consumption]]\n\n== Publications ==\n* {{cite book |last=Kardashev |first=Nikolai |title=\"On the Inevitability and the Possible Structures of Supercivilizations\" in \"The search for extraterrestrial life: Recent developments; Proceedings of the Symposium, Boston, MA, June 18\u201321, 1984\" |bibcode=1985IAUS..112..497K |pages=497\u2013504 |date=1985}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{Interstellar messages}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Kardashev, Nikolai Semenovich}}\n[[Category:1932 births]]\n[[Category:2019 deaths]]\n[[Category:Russian astrophysicists]]\n[[Category:Russian inventors]]\n[[Category:Search for extraterrestrial intelligence]]\n[[Category:Interstellar messages]]\n[[Category:Soviet astrophysicists]]\n[[Category:Moscow State University alumni]]\n[[Category:Full Members of the Russian Academy of Sciences]]\n[[Category:Radio astronomers]]\n[[Category:Demidov Prize laureates]]\n", "text_old": "'''Nikolai Semenovich Kardashev<ref>Also [[Romanization of Russian|transliterated]] '''Kardashov''', preserving the letter ''[[Yo (Cyrillic)#Russian|yo]]''.</ref>''' ({{lang-rus|\u041d\u0438\u043a\u043e\u043b\u0430\u0301\u0439 \u0421\u0435\u043c\u0451\u043d\u043e\u0432\u0438\u0447 \u041a\u0430\u0440\u0434\u0430\u0448\u0451\u0432|p=n\u02b2\u026ak\u0250\u02c8laj s\u02b2\u026a\u02c8m\u02b2\u0275n\u0259v\u02b2\u026at\u0255 k\u0259rd\u0250\u02c8\u0282of}}; 25 April 1932 \u2013 3 August 2019<ref>{{cite web|url=https://rossaprimavera.ru/news/79e0fc22|title=\u0423\u043c\u0435\u0440 \u0432\u044b\u0434\u0430\u044e\u0449\u0438\u0439\u0441\u044f \u0441\u043e\u0432\u0435\u0442\u0441\u043a\u0438\u0439 \u0430\u0441\u0442\u0440\u043e\u0444\u0438\u0437\u0438\u043a \u041d\u0438\u043a\u043e\u043b\u0430\u0439 \u041a\u0430\u0440\u0434\u0430\u0448\u0435\u0432|date=2019-08-04|publisher=\u041a\u0440\u0430\u0441\u043d\u0430\u044f \u0412\u0435\u0441\u043d\u0430|language=ru}}</ref>) was a [[Soviet Union|Soviet]] and [[Russia]]n astrophysicist, Doctor of Physical and Mathematical Sciences, and the deputy director of the [[Astro Space Center (Russia)|Astro Space Center]] of PN [[Lebedev Physical Institute]] of the [[Russian Academy of Sciences]] in Moscow.{{Infobox person\n| name               = Nikolai Kardashev\n| image              = Kardashev-e1458061627610.jpg\n| caption            = \n| birth_name         = Nikolai Semenovich Kardashev\n| birth_date         = {{birth date|1932|4|25}}\n| birth_place        = [[Moscow]], [[Russian SFSR]], [[Soviet Union]]\n| death_date         = {{death date and age|2019|8|3|1932|4|25}}\n| death_place        = [[Moscow]], [[Russia]]\n| nationality        = Soviet Union (Russia from 25 December 1991)\n| occupation         = Astrophysicist\n| years_active       = \n| known_for          = [[Kardashev scale]]\n| notable_works      = \n}}\n<br />\n\n==Early Life==\n\n# Born in Moscow to a family of professional revolutionaries involved with the [[Communist Party of the Soviet Union|Bolshevik Party]].<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://hkvalidate.perfdrive.com/captcha?ssa=6732a3b7-f249-4481-b2d8-b979db820c73&ssb=fm00f5e0iz1gph2ze3kkzd2f0&ssc=https%3A%2F%2Fiopscience.iop.org%2Farticle%2F10.3367%2FUFNe.0182.201206i.0677%2Fmeta&ssd=405741377509015&sse=cjkk@ipppcgdfng&ssf=6843b26fdf1a91859a96e59ec74c99f5cfca91f2&ssg=616b5581-078a-470a-bd7d-0c7892ae5f9d&ssh=854e7e18-5f8a-4d34-955d-27bfba365d36&ssi=8ffccafc-8427-4682-a17d-d4ac732b294f&ssj=1903d63e-48a1-4cfc-a1a2-11752a5ec723&ssk=support@shieldsquare.com&ssl=155695867491&ssm=66836733651201974102419827231121&ssn=f386fe603ac05bc65b29d6a87b074a7996ad3c2b963f-79a2-49b6-881526&sso=bfa048d1-7f444f767003d388ef5f4d6e23db539523922e70e080cf4c&ssp=39380969391588036462158802132976551&ssq=58015275559675528983755596932221824852874&ssr=MjA4LjgwLjE1My4yNA==&sss=Mozilla/4.0%20(Windows%20NT%205.1)%20AppleWebKit/535.7%20(KHTML,like%20zeco)%20Chrome/33.0.1750.154%20Safari/536.7&sst=ZoteroTranslationServer/WMF%20(mailto:services@lists.wikimedia.org)&ssu=Chrome/5.0%20(iPhone;%20U;%20CPU%20iPhone%20OS%203_0%20like%20Mac%20OS%20X;%20en-us)%20AppleWebKit/528.18%20(KHTML,%20like%20Gecko)%20Version/4.0%20Mobile/7A341%20Safari/528.16&ssv=m2qt1uuo1p1v941&ssw=&ssx=021940417581478&ssy=j@albdcjfakichhpjln@bknklonbiagpbfjeob@k&ssz=94ec63bb3fb088e|title=ShieldSquare Captcha|website=hkvalidate.perfdrive.com|doi=10.3367/ufne.0182.201206i.0677/meta|access-date=2020-04-28}}</ref>\n## Father's Name: Semen Karlovich Brike<ref name=\":0\" />\n## Mother's Name: Nina Nikolaevna Kardasheva<ref name=\":0\" />\n# His father was a prominent member of the party and his mother later joined as well before the 1917 October Revolution.<ref name=\":0\" />\n# In 1937 and 1938 (during [[Political repression in the Soviet Union|Stalin\u2019s repressions]]), both of his parents were arrested. His father was ultimately shot and his mother was forced into labor camps and would not be released for many years.<ref name=\":0\" />\n# Due to his parents\u2019 absence, he was sent to an orphanage where he then was taken by his mother\u2019s sister after a great deal of effort.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=https://asgardia.space/en/news/Astrophysics-Legend-Nikolai-Kardashev-Civilization-Ranking-Scale-Author-Died-Age-87|title=Astrophysics Legend Nikolai Kardashev, Civilization Ranking Scale Author, Died Age 87|website=asgardia.space|access-date=2020-04-28}}</ref>\n# His aunt then died during WWII when he was 16 years old and he then had to live on his own<ref name=\":1\" /> in a large communal flat.\n# His mother was released in 1956, at which point Nikolai had completed university.<ref name=\":0\" />\n# His interest in astronomy began while in 5th grade where he would attend a hobby group at the Moscow Planetarium.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n== Education ==\n\n# Moscow State. University (MGU in Russ. abbr.) - Astronomy division of the Mechanics and Mathematics Department<ref name=\":0\" />\n# Here he focus his studies/interests in radio astronomy. A field which was new and constantly developing.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n<br />\n\n== Career ==\n\n# Joined the Space Research Institute (IKI) of the USSR Academy of Sciences in 1967. <ref name=\":2\">{{Cite journal|last=I. Gurvits Leonid Joint Institute for VLBI ERIC|first=Dwingeloo|last2=Y. Kovalev Yuri Astro Space Center of Lebedev Physical Institute|first2=Moscow|last3=G. Edwards Philip CSIRO Astronomy and Space Science|first3=Marsfield|date=2019-12-16|title=Nikolai Kardashev|url=https://physicstoday.scitation.org/do/10.1063/PT.6.4o.20191216a/abs/|language=EN|doi=10.1063/PT.6.4o.20191216a}}</ref>\n# Became deputy director of IKI in 1977.<ref name=\":2\" />\n# During the dissolution of the USSR, Nikolai became the director of the Astro Space Center of the Lebedev Physical Institute.<ref name=\":2\" />\n# In 1978, Nikolai started a project called the Space VLBI mission RadioAstron. This mission covered more than 30 years and was finally launched in 2011.<ref name=\":2\" />\n## The RadioAstron mission has become one of the highlights of modern observational astrophysics.<ref name=\":2\" />\n\n== Organizations & His Role in Them<ref name=\":3\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.iau.org/administration/membership/individual/3990/|title=International Astronomical Union {{!}} IAU|website=www.iau.org|access-date=2020-04-28}}</ref><ref name=\":4\">{{Cite web|url=http://meti.org/en/blog/nikolai-kardashev-1932-2019|title=Nikolai Kardashev, 1932-2019 {{!}} METI International|website=meti.org|access-date=2020-04-28}}</ref><ref name=\":5\">{{Cite journal|last=I. Gurvits Leonid Joint Institute for VLBI ERIC|first=Dwingeloo|last2=Y. Kovalev Yuri Astro Space Center of Lebedev Physical Institute|first2=Moscow|last3=G. Edwards Philip CSIRO Astronomy and Space Science|first3=Marsfield|date=2019-12-16|title=Nikolai Kardashev|url=https://physicstoday.scitation.org/do/10.1063/PT.6.4o.20191216a/abs/|language=EN|doi=10.1063/PT.6.4o.20191216a}}</ref> ==\n\n# ''[[International Astronomical Union]]:<ref name=\":3\" />''\n## Vice-President of Executive Committee (1997-2003)<ref name=\":3\" />\n## Vice-President of Commission 51 Bio-Astronomy (1982-1991)<ref name=\":3\" />\n## Organizing Committee Member of Commission 40 Radio Astronomy (1967-1985)<ref name=\":3\" />\n## Member of Division B Facilities, Technologies and Data Science (2019)<ref name=\":3\" />\n## Member of Division F Planetary Systems and Astrobiology (2019)<ref name=\":3\" />\n## Member of Commission 40 Radio Astronomy (2015)<ref name=\":3\" />\n## Member of Commission 51 Bio-Astronomy (2015)<ref name=\":3\" />\n## Member of Division III Planetary Systems Sciences (2012)<ref name=\":3\" />\n## Member of Division X Radio Astronomy (2012)<ref name=\":3\" />\n## Member of Special Nominating Committee (2000-2003)<ref name=\":3\" />\n# ''[[Academy of Sciences of the Soviet Union|USSR Academy of Sciences]], Division of General Physics and Astronomy:''<ref name=\":4\" />\n## Corresponding (associate) member (December 12th 1976)<ref name=\":4\" />\n## Full Member (March 21st 1994)<ref name=\":4\" />\n## Served as chair of the Russion Academy of Sciences Council on Astronomy (1999-death)<ref name=\":4\" />\n# [[Committee on Space Research]]<ref name=\":5\" />\n## Vice President of the Committee for Space Research from 1982-1986.<ref name=\":5\" />\n\n== Scientific Career ==\n\n# Discoveries\n## Kardashev scale - 1964<ref name=\":5\" />\n## VLBI - Very Long Baseline Interferometry<ref name=\":5\" />\n### This replaced conventional radio transmission lines with magnetic tape recordings. Demonstrated in 1967<ref name=\":5\" />\n# Awards and Honors\n## 1988 - Shared the USSR's State Prize for the discovery of Radio Recombination Lines.<ref name=\":5\" />\n## In 2012, Nikolai received the Grote Reber Gold Medal for innovative lifetime contributions to radio astronomy.<ref name=\":5\" />\n# Published Works\n## 1963 - \"Candidate of Science\" dissertation, later promoted to higher level of doctoral thesis.<ref name=\":5\" />\n## 1964 - \u201cTransmission of Information by Extraterrestrial Civilizations\u201d<ref name=\":5\" />\n### Presented the classification of civilizations based on their level of power consumption spanning 20 orders of magnitude. Became known as Kardashev Scale.<ref name=\":5\" />\n\n== Film Career<ref name=\":6\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.imdb.com/name/nm9914444/|title=Nikolai Kardashev|website=IMDb|access-date=2020-04-28}}</ref> ==\n\n# His first connection with the film industry was in 1981. He was asked to be a consultant on the set of Petyla Oriona a Russian tv series documentary.<ref name=\":6\" />\n# Played himself in a tv show episode on the documentary series \"Spaces Deepest Secrets\" in 2018.<ref name=\":6\" />\n# Played himself in a tv show episode on the documentary series \"Horizon\" in 2018.<ref name=\":6\" />\n\n<br />\n\n== Extraterrestrial Research ==\n\n# May have predicted the existence of pulsars before they were officially discovered.<ref name=\":0\" />\n# \u2018Transmission of Information by Extraterrestrial Civilizations'<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n<br />\n\n== Death ==\n\n# Passed away on August 3rd 2019 at the age of 87.<ref name=\":1\" />\n\n==See also==\n* [[Kardashev scale]]\n* [[Astroengineering]]\n* [[Drake equation]]\n* [[SETI]]\n* [[Planetary civilization]]\n* [[Orders of magnitude (power)]]\n* [[Orders of magnitude (energy)]]\n* [[Technological singularity]]\n* [[World energy resources and consumption]]\n\n== Publications ==\n* {{cite book |last=Kardashev |first=Nikolai |title=\"On the Inevitability and the Possible Structures of Supercivilizations\" in \"The search for extraterrestrial life: Recent developments; Proceedings of the Symposium, Boston, MA, June 18\u201321, 1984\" |bibcode=1985IAUS..112..497K |pages=497\u2013504 |date=1985}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{Interstellar messages}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Kardashev, Nikolai Semenovich}}\n[[Category:1932 births]]\n[[Category:2019 deaths]]\n[[Category:Russian astrophysicists]]\n[[Category:Russian inventors]]\n[[Category:Search for extraterrestrial intelligence]]\n[[Category:Interstellar messages]]\n[[Category:Soviet astrophysicists]]\n[[Category:Moscow State University alumni]]\n[[Category:Full Members of the Russian Academy of Sciences]]\n[[Category:Radio astronomers]]\n[[Category:Demidov Prize laureates]]\n", "name_user": "Arjayay", "label": "safe", "comment": "Sp", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Nikolai_Kardashev"}
{"title_page": "Zukiswa Wanner", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=August 2016}}\n{{Use South African English|date=August 2016}}\n'''Zukiswa Wanner''' (born 1976) is a [[South African people|South African]] journalist and novelist, born in [[Zambia]] and now based in [[Kenya]]. Since 2006, when she published her first book, her novels have been shortlisted for awards including the [[South African Literary Awards (SALA)]] and the [[Commonwealth Writers' Prize]]. In 2015, she won the [[K Sello Duiker Memorial Literary Award]] for ''London Cape Town Joburg'' (2014).<ref name=\"bookslive.co.za\">[http://bookslive.co.za/blog/2015/11/09/2015-south-african-literary-awards-salas-winners-announced/ \"2015 South African Literary Awards (SALAs) Winners Announced\"], Books Live, ''Sunday Times'', 9 November 2015.</ref> In 2014 Wanner was named on the [[Africa39]] list of 39 Sub-Saharan African writers aged under 40 with potential and talent to define trends in African literature.<ref name=Africa39>[http://www.hayfestival.com/artistlist-u-x.aspx Africa39 list of artists], Hay Festival.</ref> In 2020 Wanner was awarded the [[Goethe Medal]] alongside [[Ian McEwan]] and [[Elvira Espejo Ayca]], making Wanner the first African woman to win the award.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://literandra.com/first-african-woman-to-be-awarded-the-goethe-medal-zukiswa-wanner/|title=First African Woman to Be Awarded the Goethe Medal: Zukiswa Wanner|date=2020-04-28|website=Literandra|language=en-GB|access-date=2020-04-29}}</ref>\n\n==Life and career==\nZukiswa Wanner was born in 1976 in [[Lusaka]], [[Zambia]], to a South African father and a Zimbabwean mother.<ref name=Kwela>[http://www.kwela.com/authors/5115 Biographical info: Zukiswa Wanner], Kwela.</ref> After receiving primary and secondary education in [[Zimbabwe]], she studied for a degree in journalism at [[Hawaii Pacific University]] in [[Honolulu]].\n\nHer [[debut novel]], ''The Madams'', was published in 2006 and has been called \"a racy and hilarious take on the black economic empowerment crowd in Johannesburg\".<ref>[http://www.theafricareport.com/Society-and-Culture/book-releases-men-of-the-south-by-zukiswa-wanner.html \"Book Releases: Men of the South by Zukiswa Wanner\"], ''The Africa Report'', 28 June 2011.</ref> It was shortlisted for the [[K Sello Duiker Award]] of the South African Literary Awards (SALA) in 2007.<ref name=Guardian>[https://www.theguardian.com/profile/zukiswa-wanner Profile: Zukiswa Wanner], ''The Guardian''.</ref> She went on to write three other novels: ''Behind Every Successful Man'' (2008), ''Men of the South'' (2010), which was shortlisted for the 2011 [[Commonwealth Writers' Prize]] (Africa region),<ref>[http://www.commonwealthfoundation.com/NewsArticle.aspx?articleID=146 2011 Commonwealth Writers' Prize shortlists announced] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120528122629/http://www.commonwealthfoundation.com/NewsArticle.aspx?articleID=146 |date=28 May 2012 }}, 11 February 2011.</ref> as well as the Herman Charles Bosman Award,<ref>[https://www.hayfestival.com/artist.aspx?artistid=5999 \"Zukiswa Wanner\"], Hay Festival.</ref><ref name=AfricaBookClub>Daniel Musiiitwa, [http://www.africabookclub.com/?p=13721 \"Zukiswa Wanner\"] Africa Book Club, 4 July 2013.</ref> and 2014's ''London Cape Town Joburg'', which won the K Sello Duiker Memorial Literary Award in 2015.<ref name=\"bookslive.co.za\"/>\n\nIn 2010, she co-authored two works of non-fiction: with South African photographer [[Alf Kumalo]] ''A Prisoner's Home'', a biography on the first Mandela house 8115 Vilakazi Street, and ''L'Esprit du Sport'' with French photographer Amelie Debray. Wanner is co-editor of the African-Asian short-story anthology ''Behind the Shadows'' (2012) with Rohini Chowdhury.<ref name=AfricaBookClub /> In addition Wanner has written two children's books, ''Jama Loves Bananas'' and ''Refilwe'' \u2013 an African retelling of the fairy tale \"[[Rapunzel]]\". In 2018, her third nonfiction work ''Hardly Working'' a travel memoir was published by Black Letter Media.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://brittlepaper.com/2018/02/zukiswa-wanners-memoir-working-adventurefilled-personal/|title=Zukiswa Wanner's Travel Memoir, \"Hardly Working,\" Is Adventure-filled and Personal|date=2018-02-23|website=Brittle Paper|access-date=2020-04-28}}</ref>\n\nShe was one of 66 writers to write a contemporary response to the Bible, the works being staged at the [[Bush Theatre]] and at [[Westminster Abbey]] in October 2011.<ref>[https://www.amazon.co.uk/Sixty-Six-Books-21st-century-writers-speak/dp/1849432279 ''Sixty-Six Books: 21st-century writers speak to the King James Bible''], [[Oberon Books]], 2011, {{ISBN|978-1849432276}}.</ref>\n\nShe is a founding member of the ReadSA initiative, a campaign encouraging South Africans to read South African works.<ref name=Kwela/><ref name=Guardian/> She also sat on the pan-African literary initiative, Writivism's Board of Trustees until September 2016. She is a regular participant at international literary events and has conducted workshops for young writers in Zimbabwe, South Africa, Denmark, Germany and Western Kenya.<ref name=AfricaBookClub /><ref name=Amazon />\n\nWanner was also one of three judges of the sole Pan-African literary prize for book-length fiction, the [[Etisalat Prize for Literature]] in 2015 and the African juror for the Commonwealth Short Story Prize 2017. She has also been the founder and curator of Artistic Encounters in Nairobi, Kenya. In 2020 she founded and curated the [[Afrolit Sans Frontieres Festival]] as part of the COVID-19 lockdown. The festival featured prominent African writers like [[Maaza Mengiste]], [[Fred Khumalo]], [[Chris Abani]], [[Yvonne Adhiambo Owuor]], [[Shadreck Chikoti]], [[Abubakar Adam Ibrahim]], [[M\u0169koma wa Ng\u0169g\u0129]], [[Jennifer Nansubuga Makumbi]], [[Mona Eltahawy]], [[Nii Parkes|Nii Ayikwei Parkes]], [[Sulaiman Addonia]], [[Chike Frankie Edozien]], [[Lola Shoneyin]] among others.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://mg.co.za/article/2020-03-23-afrolit-sans-frontieres-stories-and-writers-in-the-comfort-of-your-living-room/|title=Afrolit Sans Fronti\u00e8res: Stories and writers in the comfort of your living room|date=2020-03-23|website=The Mail & Guardian|language=en-ZA|access-date=2020-04-26}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://brittlepaper.com/2020/04/highlights-from-the-afrolit-sans-frontieres-virtual-literary-festival/|title=Highlights from the Afrolit Sans Fronti\u00e8res Virtual Literary Festival|date=2020-04-08|website=Brittle Paper|access-date=2020-04-26}}</ref>\n\nIn 2018, she set up her publishing company, Paivapo, in partnership with her friend and businessperson Nomavuso Vokwana<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://paivapo.africa/about-founders/|title=About founders|date=2018-10-18|website=Paivapo Publishers|language=en-GB|access-date=2020-04-26}}</ref> with a focus on marketing African literature in the Anglophone, Francophone and Lusophone African regions.<ref>Jennifer Malec, [https://johannesburgreviewofbooks.com/2018/04/19/the-jrb-daily-exclusive-to-the-jrb-im-going-to-market-the-hell-out-of-our-stories-zukiswa-wanner-reveals-the-details-of-her-new-africa-focused-publishing-company-paivapo/ \"Exclusive to The JRB: 'I'm going to market the hell out of our stories'\u2014Zukiswa Wanner reveals the details of her new Africa-focused publishing company, Paivapo\"], ''The Johannesburg Review of Books'', 19 April 2018.</ref><ref>[[Abubakar Adam Ibrahim]], [https://www.dailytrust.com.ng/zukiswa-wanner-floats-afro-centric-publishing-house.html \"Zukiswa Wanner floats Afro-centric publishing house\"], ''Daily Trust'', 22 April 2018.</ref>\n\nA prolific journalist, essayist and short story writer, she has been a contributor to a wide range of newspapers and magazines, including ''[[The Observer]]''/''[[The Guardian]]'', ''Sunday Independent'', ''[[City Press (South Africa)|City Press]]'', ''[[Mail & Guardian]]'', ''La Republica'', ''Open Society'', ''[[The Sunday Times]]'', ''African Review'', ''[[New Statesman]]'', ''True Love'', ''[[Marie Claire]]'', ''Real'', ''Juice'', ''OpenSpace'', ''Wordsetc'', ''Baobab'', ''Shape'', ''[[Oprah magazine|Oprah]]'', ''[[Elle magazine|Elle]]'', ''Juice'', ''[[Guernica (magazine)|Guernica]]'', ''Afropolitan'' and ''[[Forbes|Forbes Africa]]''.<ref name=AfricaBookClub /><ref name=Amazon>[https://www.amazon.com/Zukiswa-Wanner/e/B001JP3WGY/ref=dp_byline_cont_ebooks_1 Zukiswa Wanner page] at Amazon.</ref><ref>[http://www.sahistory.org.za/article/women-african-literature-writing-and-representation \"Women in African Literature: Writing and Representation\"], South African History Online.</ref> Her writing is also included in the 2019 anthology ''[[New Daughters of Africa]]'', edited by [[Margaret Busby]].<ref>Michele Magwood, [https://www.wantedonline.co.za/navigator/leisure/2019-07-05-new-daughters-of-africa-is-a-powerful-collection-of-writing-by-women-from-the-continent/ \"'New Daughters of Africa' Is a Powerful Collection of Writing by Women from the Continent\"], ''Wanted'', 5 July 2019.</ref>\n\nWanner currently lives in [[Nairobi]], [[Kenya]], having visited for the first time in 2008 and moved there three years later.<ref>Zukiswa Wanner, [http://www.nation.co.ke/lifestyle/weekend/WANNER-How-Zimbabwe-and-Kenya-became-one-people/1220-3201992-eyypviz/index.html \"Two nations and how Zimbabwe and Kenya became one people\"], ''Daily Nation'', 13 May 2006.</ref>\n\n== Awards and honours ==\nIn April 2014, Wanner was named on the [[Hay Festival]]'s [[Africa39]] list of 39 Sub-Saharan African writers aged under 40 with potential and talent to define trends in African literature.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.hayfestival.com/artistlist-u-x.aspx|title=List of Artists - Hay Festival 2020|website=www.hayfestival.com|access-date=2020-04-28}}</ref>\n\nIn 2015, she won the [[K Sello Duiker Memorial Literary Award]] for ''London Cape Town Joburg'' (2014).\n\nIn 2020, Wanner was awarded the Goethe Medal, a yearly prize given by the [[Goethe-Institut]] honoring non-Germans \"who have performed outstanding service for the German language and for international cultural relations\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.goethe.de/en/uun/ver/gme/prt.html|title=Awardees - Goethe-Institut|website=www.goethe.de|access-date=2020-04-28}}</ref>\n\n==Bibliography==\n\n===Novels===\n* ''The Madams'', Oshun Books, 2006. {{ISBN|978-1770070585}}\n* ''Behind Every Successful Man'', Kwela Books, 2008. {{ISBN|978-0795702617}}\n* ''Men of the South'', Kwela Books, 2010. {{ISBN|978-0795702983}}\n* ''London Cape Town Joburg'', Kwela Books, 2014\n\n===Non-fiction===\n* ''8115: A Prisoner's Home with Alf Kumalo'', Penguin, 2010\n* ''Maid in SA: 30 Ways to Leave Your Madam'', Jacana, 2010. {{ISBN|978-1431408962}}\n* ''Hardly Working'': ''A Travel Memoir of Sorts,'' Black Letter Media, 2018.\n\n===Children's books===\n* ''Jama Loves Bananas'', Jacana, 2013\n* ''Refilwe'' (an African retelling of \"[[Rapunzel]]\"), Jacana, 2014\n\n===As editor===\n* With Rohini Chowdhury, ''Behind The Shadows. Contemporary Stories from Africa and Asia'' (2012)\n\n==Awards==\n* Twenty in 20 best stories in South African literature.<ref>[http://bookslive.co.za/blog/2014/07/22/the-twenty-in-20-final-list-the-best-short-stories-of-south-africa%E2%80%99s-democracy/ \"The Twenty in 20 Final List: the Best Short Stories of South Africa's Democracy\"], Books Live, ''Sunday Times'', 22 July 2014.</ref>\n* [[South African Literary Awards (SALA)]] \u2014 K Sello Duiker Prize 2015 for ''London Cape Town Joburg''\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n* Ambrose Musiyiwa, [http://conversationswithwriters.blogspot.co.uk/2008/11/interview-zukiswa-wanner-author-of.html Zukiswa Wanner: Interview 1], ''Conversations with Writers'', November 2008.\n* Janet van Eeden, [https://archive.is/20121224160321/http://www.argief.litnet.co.za/cgi-bin/giga.cgi?cmd=cause_dir_news_item&cause_id=1270&news_id=91320 Zukiswa Wanner, author of Men of the South], ''LitNet'', 17 August 2010.\n* [http://vasigauke.blogspot.co.uk/2011/01/reading-2010-zukiswa-wanner-south.html \"Reading 2010: Zukiswa Wanner (South Africa)\"], ''Wealth of Ideas'', 1 February 2011.\n* [http://geosireads.wordpress.com/2011/02/17/in-a-conversation-with-south-african-writer-zukiswa-wanner/ In a Conversation with South African Writer, Zukiswa Wanner], ''Geosi Reads'', 17 February 2011.\n* Ambrose Musiyiwa, [http://conversationswithwriters.blogspot.co.uk/2011/02/interview2-zukiswa-wanner.html Zukiswa Wanner: Interview 2], ''Conversations with Writers'', 19 February 2011.\n* Kiprop Kimutai, [https://jalada.org/jalada-conversations/the-jalada-conversations-no-4-zukiswa-wanner/ \"The Jalada Conversations No 4: Zukiswa Wanner\"], 30 November 2015. Jalada, a pan-African writers' collective.\n* Exclusive to The JRB: '[https://johannesburgreviewofbooks.com/2018/04/19/the-jrb-daily-exclusive-to-the-jrb-im-going-to-market-the-hell-out-of-our-stories-zukiswa-wanner-reveals-the-details-of-her-new-africa-focused-publishing-company-paivapo/ I'm going to market the hell out of our stories]' \u2014Zukiswa Wanner reveals the details of her new Africa-focused publishing company, Paivapo\n* [https://johannesburgreviewofbooks.com/2017/10/02/page-19-a-border-tale-of-visas-and-eastern-europe-by-zukiswa-wanner/ A border tale of visas and Eastern Europe] by Zukiswa Wanner\n* ''Artistic Encounters'' featuring [https://www.goethe.de/ins/ke/en/ver.cfm?fuseaction=events.detail&event_id=21288463 Niq Mhlongo & Nick Ndeda]'''.'''\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Wanner, Zukiswa}}\n[[Category:South African women novelists]]\n[[Category:South African journalists]]\n[[Category:1976 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:21st-century South African novelists]]\n[[Category:21st-century South African women writers]]\n[[Category:21st-century essayists]]\n[[Category:South African children's writers]]\n[[Category:Hawaii Pacific University alumni]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=August 2016}}\n{{Use South African English|date=August 2016}}\n'''Zukiswa Wanner''' (born 1976) is a [[South African people|South African]] journalist and novelist, born in [[Zambia]] and now based in [[Kenya]]. Since 2006, when she published her first book, her novels have been shortlisted for awards including the [[South African Literary Awards (SALA)]] and the [[Commonwealth Writers' Prize]]. In 2015, she won the [[K Sello Duiker Memorial Literary Award]] for ''London Cape Town Joburg'' (2014).<ref name=\"bookslive.co.za\">[http://bookslive.co.za/blog/2015/11/09/2015-south-african-literary-awards-salas-winners-announced/ \"2015 South African Literary Awards (SALAs) Winners Announced\"], Books Live, ''Sunday Times'', 9 November 2015.</ref> In 2014 Wanner was named on the [[Africa39]] list of 39 Sub-Saharan African writers aged under 40 with potential and talent to define trends in African literature.<ref name=Africa39>[http://www.hayfestival.com/artistlist-u-x.aspx Africa39 list of artists], Hay Festival.</ref> In 2020 Wanner was awarded the [[Goethe Medal]] alongside [[Ian McEwan]] and [[Elvira Espejo Ayca]].\n\n==Life==\nZukiswa Wanner was born in 1976 in [[Lusaka]], [[Zambia]], to a South African father and a Zimbabwean mother.<ref name=Kwela>[http://www.kwela.com/authors/5115 Biographical info: Zukiswa Wanner], Kwela.</ref> After receiving primary and secondary education in [[Zimbabwe]], she studied for a degree in journalism at [[Hawaii Pacific University]] in [[Honolulu]].\n\nHer [[debut novel]], ''The Madams'', was published in 2006 and has been called \"a racy and hilarious take on the black economic empowerment crowd in Johannesburg\".<ref>[http://www.theafricareport.com/Society-and-Culture/book-releases-men-of-the-south-by-zukiswa-wanner.html \"Book Releases: Men of the South by Zukiswa Wanner\"], ''The Africa Report'', 28 June 2011.</ref> It was shortlisted for the [[K Sello Duiker Award]] of the South African Literary Awards (SALA) in 2007.<ref name=Guardian>[https://www.theguardian.com/profile/zukiswa-wanner Profile: Zukiswa Wanner], ''The Guardian''.</ref> She went on to write three other novels: ''Behind Every Successful Man'' (2008), ''Men of the South'' (2010), which was shortlisted for the 2011 [[Commonwealth Writers' Prize]] (Africa region),<ref>[http://www.commonwealthfoundation.com/NewsArticle.aspx?articleID=146 2011 Commonwealth Writers' Prize shortlists announced] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120528122629/http://www.commonwealthfoundation.com/NewsArticle.aspx?articleID=146 |date=28 May 2012 }}, 11 February 2011.</ref> as well as the Herman Charles Bosman Award,<ref>[https://www.hayfestival.com/artist.aspx?artistid=5999 \"Zukiswa Wanner\"], Hay Festival.</ref><ref name=AfricaBookClub>Daniel Musiiitwa, [http://www.africabookclub.com/?p=13721 \"Zukiswa Wanner\"] Africa Book Club, 4 July 2013.</ref> and 2014's ''London Cape Town Joburg'', which won the K Sello Duiker Memorial Literary Award in 2015.<ref name=\"bookslive.co.za\"/>\n\nIn 2010, she co-authored two works of non-fiction: with South African photographer [[Alf Kumalo]] ''A Prisoner's Home'', a biography on the first Mandela house 8115 Vilakazi Street, and ''L'Esprit du Sport'' with French photographer Amelie Debray. Wanner is co-editor of the African-Asian short-story anthology ''Behind the Shadows'' (2012) with Rohini Chowdhury.<ref name=AfricaBookClub /> In addition Wanner has written two children's books, ''Jama Loves Bananas'' and ''Refilwe'' \u2013 an African retelling of the fairy tale \"[[Rapunzel]]\". In 2018, her third nonfiction work ''Hardly Working'' a travel memoir was published by Black Letter Media.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://brittlepaper.com/2018/02/zukiswa-wanners-memoir-working-adventurefilled-personal/|title=Zukiswa Wanner's Travel Memoir, \"Hardly Working,\" Is Adventure-filled and Personal|date=2018-02-23|website=Brittle Paper|access-date=2020-04-28}}</ref>\n\nShe was one of 66 writers to write a contemporary response to the Bible, the works being staged at the [[Bush Theatre]] and at [[Westminster Abbey]] in October 2011.<ref>[https://www.amazon.co.uk/Sixty-Six-Books-21st-century-writers-speak/dp/1849432279 ''Sixty-Six Books: 21st-century writers speak to the King James Bible''], [[Oberon Books]], 2011, {{ISBN|978-1849432276}}.</ref>\n\nShe is a founding member of the ReadSA initiative, a campaign encouraging South Africans to read South African works.<ref name=Kwela/><ref name=Guardian/> She also sat on the pan-African literary initiative, Writivism's Board of Trustees until September 2016. She is a regular participant at international literary events and has conducted workshops for young writers in Zimbabwe, South Africa, Denmark, Germany and Western Kenya.<ref name=AfricaBookClub /><ref name=Amazon />\n\nWanner was also one of three judges of the sole Pan-African literary prize for book-length fiction, the [[Etisalat Prize for Literature]] in 2015 and the African juror for the Commonwealth Short Story Prize 2017. She has also been the founder and curator of Artistic Encounters in Nairobi, Kenya. In 2020 she founded and curated the [[Afrolit Sans Frontieres Festival]] as part of the COVID-19 lockdown. The festival featured prominent African writers like [[Maaza Mengiste]], [[Fred Khumalo]], [[Chris Abani]], [[Yvonne Adhiambo Owuor]], [[Shadreck Chikoti]], [[Abubakar Adam Ibrahim]], [[M\u0169koma wa Ng\u0169g\u0129]], [[Jennifer Nansubuga Makumbi]], [[Mona Eltahawy]], [[Nii Parkes|Nii Ayikwei Parkes]], [[Sulaiman Addonia]], [[Chike Frankie Edozien]], [[Lola Shoneyin]] among others.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://mg.co.za/article/2020-03-23-afrolit-sans-frontieres-stories-and-writers-in-the-comfort-of-your-living-room/|title=Afrolit Sans Fronti\u00e8res: Stories and writers in the comfort of your living room|date=2020-03-23|website=The Mail & Guardian|language=en-ZA|access-date=2020-04-26}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://brittlepaper.com/2020/04/highlights-from-the-afrolit-sans-frontieres-virtual-literary-festival/|title=Highlights from the Afrolit Sans Fronti\u00e8res Virtual Literary Festival|date=2020-04-08|website=Brittle Paper|access-date=2020-04-26}}</ref>\n\nIn 2018, she set up her publishing company, Paivapo, in partnership with her friend and businessperson Nomavuso Vokwana<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://paivapo.africa/about-founders/|title=About founders|date=2018-10-18|website=Paivapo Publishers|language=en-GB|access-date=2020-04-26}}</ref> with a focus on marketing African literature in the Anglophone, Francophone and Lusophone African regions.<ref>Jennifer Malec, [https://johannesburgreviewofbooks.com/2018/04/19/the-jrb-daily-exclusive-to-the-jrb-im-going-to-market-the-hell-out-of-our-stories-zukiswa-wanner-reveals-the-details-of-her-new-africa-focused-publishing-company-paivapo/ \"Exclusive to The JRB: 'I'm going to market the hell out of our stories'\u2014Zukiswa Wanner reveals the details of her new Africa-focused publishing company, Paivapo\"], ''The Johannesburg Review of Books'', 19 April 2018.</ref><ref>[[Abubakar Adam Ibrahim]], [https://www.dailytrust.com.ng/zukiswa-wanner-floats-afro-centric-publishing-house.html \"Zukiswa Wanner floats Afro-centric publishing house\"], ''Daily Trust'', 22 April 2018.</ref>\n\nA prolific journalist, essayist and short story writer, she has been a contributor to a wide range of newspapers and magazines, including ''[[The Observer]]''/''[[The Guardian]]'', ''Sunday Independent'', ''[[City Press (South Africa)|City Press]]'', ''[[Mail & Guardian]]'', ''La Republica'', ''Open Society'', ''[[The Sunday Times]]'', ''African Review'', ''[[New Statesman]]'', ''True Love'', ''[[Marie Claire]]'', ''Real'', ''Juice'', ''OpenSpace'', ''Wordsetc'', ''Baobab'', ''Shape'', ''[[Oprah magazine|Oprah]]'', ''[[Elle magazine|Elle]]'', ''Juice'', ''[[Guernica (magazine)|Guernica]]'', ''Afropolitan'' and ''[[Forbes|Forbes Africa]]''.<ref name=AfricaBookClub /><ref name=Amazon>[https://www.amazon.com/Zukiswa-Wanner/e/B001JP3WGY/ref=dp_byline_cont_ebooks_1 Zukiswa Wanner page] at Amazon.</ref><ref>[http://www.sahistory.org.za/article/women-african-literature-writing-and-representation \"Women in African Literature: Writing and Representation\"], South African History Online.</ref> Her writing is also included in the 2019 anthology ''[[New Daughters of Africa]]'', edited by [[Margaret Busby]].<ref>Michele Magwood, [https://www.wantedonline.co.za/navigator/leisure/2019-07-05-new-daughters-of-africa-is-a-powerful-collection-of-writing-by-women-from-the-continent/ \"'New Daughters of Africa' Is a Powerful Collection of Writing by Women from the Continent\"], ''Wanted'', 5 July 2019.</ref>\n\nWanner currently lives in [[Nairobi]], [[Kenya]], having visited for the first time in 2008 and moved there three years later.<ref>Zukiswa Wanner, [http://www.nation.co.ke/lifestyle/weekend/WANNER-How-Zimbabwe-and-Kenya-became-one-people/1220-3201992-eyypviz/index.html \"Two nations and how Zimbabwe and Kenya became one people\"], ''Daily Nation'', 13 May 2006.</ref>\n\n== Awards and honours ==\nIn April 2014, Wanner was named on the [[Hay Festival]]'s [[Africa39]] list of 39 Sub-Saharan African writers aged under 40 with potential and talent to define trends in African literature.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.hayfestival.com/artistlist-u-x.aspx|title=List of Artists - Hay Festival 2020|website=www.hayfestival.com|access-date=2020-04-28}}</ref>\n\nIn 2015, she won the [[K Sello Duiker Memorial Literary Award]] for ''London Cape Town Joburg'' (2014).\n\nIn 2020, Wanner was awarded the Goethe Medal, a yearly prize given by the [[Goethe-Institut]] honoring non-Germans \"who have performed outstanding service for the German language and for international cultural relations\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.goethe.de/en/uun/ver/gme/prt.html|title=Awardees - Goethe-Institut|website=www.goethe.de|access-date=2020-04-28}}</ref>\n\n==Bibliography==\n\n===Novels===\n* ''The Madams'', Oshun Books, 2006. {{ISBN|978-1770070585}}\n* ''Behind Every Successful Man'', Kwela Books, 2008. {{ISBN|978-0795702617}}\n* ''Men of the South'', Kwela Books, 2010. {{ISBN|978-0795702983}}\n* ''London Cape Town Joburg'', Kwela Books, 2014\n\n===Non-fiction===\n* ''8115: A Prisoner's Home with Alf Kumalo'', Penguin, 2010\n* ''Maid in SA: 30 Ways to Leave Your Madam'', Jacana, 2010. {{ISBN|978-1431408962}}\n* ''Hardly Working'': ''A Travel Memoir of Sorts,'' Black Letter Media, 2018.\n\n===Children's books===\n* ''Jama Loves Bananas'', Jacana, 2013\n* ''Refilwe'' (an African retelling of \"[[Rapunzel]]\"), Jacana, 2014\n\n===As editor===\n* With Rohini Chowdhury, ''Behind The Shadows. Contemporary Stories from Africa and Asia'' (2012)\n\n==Awards==\n* Twenty in 20 best stories in South African literature.<ref>[http://bookslive.co.za/blog/2014/07/22/the-twenty-in-20-final-list-the-best-short-stories-of-south-africa%E2%80%99s-democracy/ \"The Twenty in 20 Final List: the Best Short Stories of South Africa's Democracy\"], Books Live, ''Sunday Times'', 22 July 2014.</ref>\n* [[South African Literary Awards (SALA)]] \u2014 K Sello Duiker Prize 2015 for ''London Cape Town Joburg''\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n* Ambrose Musiyiwa, [http://conversationswithwriters.blogspot.co.uk/2008/11/interview-zukiswa-wanner-author-of.html Zukiswa Wanner: Interview 1], ''Conversations with Writers'', November 2008.\n* Janet van Eeden, [https://archive.is/20121224160321/http://www.argief.litnet.co.za/cgi-bin/giga.cgi?cmd=cause_dir_news_item&cause_id=1270&news_id=91320 Zukiswa Wanner, author of Men of the South], ''LitNet'', 17 August 2010.\n* [http://vasigauke.blogspot.co.uk/2011/01/reading-2010-zukiswa-wanner-south.html \"Reading 2010: Zukiswa Wanner (South Africa)\"], ''Wealth of Ideas'', 1 February 2011.\n* [http://geosireads.wordpress.com/2011/02/17/in-a-conversation-with-south-african-writer-zukiswa-wanner/ In a Conversation with South African Writer, Zukiswa Wanner], ''Geosi Reads'', 17 February 2011.\n* Ambrose Musiyiwa, [http://conversationswithwriters.blogspot.co.uk/2011/02/interview2-zukiswa-wanner.html Zukiswa Wanner: Interview 2], ''Conversations with Writers'', 19 February 2011.\n* Kiprop Kimutai, [https://jalada.org/jalada-conversations/the-jalada-conversations-no-4-zukiswa-wanner/ \"The Jalada Conversations No 4: Zukiswa Wanner\"], 30 November 2015. Jalada, a pan-African writers' collective.\n* Exclusive to The JRB: '[https://johannesburgreviewofbooks.com/2018/04/19/the-jrb-daily-exclusive-to-the-jrb-im-going-to-market-the-hell-out-of-our-stories-zukiswa-wanner-reveals-the-details-of-her-new-africa-focused-publishing-company-paivapo/ I'm going to market the hell out of our stories]' \u2014Zukiswa Wanner reveals the details of her new Africa-focused publishing company, Paivapo\n* [https://johannesburgreviewofbooks.com/2017/10/02/page-19-a-border-tale-of-visas-and-eastern-europe-by-zukiswa-wanner/ A border tale of visas and Eastern Europe] by Zukiswa Wanner\n* ''Artistic Encounters'' featuring [https://www.goethe.de/ins/ke/en/ver.cfm?fuseaction=events.detail&event_id=21288463 Niq Mhlongo & Nick Ndeda]'''.'''\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Wanner, Zukiswa}}\n[[Category:South African women novelists]]\n[[Category:South African journalists]]\n[[Category:1976 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:21st-century South African novelists]]\n[[Category:21st-century South African women writers]]\n[[Category:21st-century essayists]]\n[[Category:South African children's writers]]\n[[Category:Hawaii Pacific University alumni]]\n", "name_user": "African Literati", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Zukiswa_Wanner"}
{"title_page": "Pedro Costa (musician)", "text_new": "{{Other people|Pedro Costa}}\n{{Use Canadian English|date=September 2014}}\n{{Infobox musical artist <!-- See Wikipedia:WikiProject_Musicians -->\n| name                = Pedro Costa\n| background          = solo_singer\n| image               = Pedro_Composer.jpg\n| image_size          =\n| alt                 =\n| caption             =\n| birth_name          =\n| alias               =\n| birth_date          = \n| birth_place         =\n| origin              = \n| genre               = {{hlist|[[indie rock]]|[[indie folk]]|[[Electronic music|electronic]]}}\n| occupation          =\n| instrument          =\n| years_active        = 2008\u2013present\n| label               =\n| associated_acts     = Fetal Pulse, Dove Pilot\n| url                 = {{URL|pedrocosta.com}}\n}}\n\n'''Pedro Costa''' is a Canadian television composer, and music producer. He first achieved notability in [[Poland]] where he received national airplay, and had two songs in the Polish singles chart.\n\n==Biography==\n\n===Projects===\nDriven by his passion for songwriting Pedro's solo recording debut came in 2008 with the Portuguese single \"A beira da estrada\". This was the followed by his first Alternative Rock EP \"The Light\". \n\nRecorded in 2009, it has generated Pedro's biggest success to date. Discovered online by Polish radio producer and personality [[:pl:Piotr Baron (dziennikarz)|Piotr Baron]] the song went on to chart in Poland's singles chart. The Light reached a peek position of 11th on 5 May 2009 (see Charts). And was ranked 85th overall for 2009.<ref>{{cite web|title=2009 Polish singles of the year|url=http://www.lp3.pl/alpt.phtml?m=27&pr=2009#ttabl}}</ref> According to Costa, \"The Light\" was also played nationally in Portugal by [[R\u00e1dio Renascen\u00e7a]].<ref>{{cite web|title=The Light on R\u00e1dio Renascen\u00e7a|url=http://www.pedrocosta.com/2009/06/15/radio-renascenca-featured-the-light/|last=Costa|first=Pedro}}</ref> \n\nSome success also came in Costa's native Canada. In 2010 \"Fooled Again?\" was discovered by CBC radio producer [[Amanda Putz]] and featured on CBC Radio 1 show ''[[Bandwidth (radio program)|Bandwidth]]''. The track also made the CBC radio 3 track of the day.<ref name=\"radio3.cbc.ca1\" />\nAfter several other singles releases and collaborative efforts his first full-length album \"Discovery\" was released March 2011.\n\n===Film and TV licensing===\nHis first TV licensing deal came from an original rendition of the song, \"God\u2019s Gonna Cut You Down\" on Discovery Channel's show \"Weed Country\".\nIn 2017 the critically acclaimed Netflix show 13 Reason Why used Pedro's song \"Finding My Wings\" on the show's soundtrack.<ref>{{cite web|title=13 Reasons Why soundtrack|url=https://www.tunefind.com/show/13-reasons-why/season-1/42514#songs}}</ref>\n\n==Discography==\n\n===Solo Releases===\n*''Made for TV'' (2015)\n*''Discovery'' (2011)\n*Pie In The Sky (2010) (EP)\n*The Light (2009) (EP)\n\n===Fetal Pulse===\n*Synthetica (2015) (EP)\n*''Space'' (2013)\n*''Cityscapes'' (2011)\n\n===Dove Pilot===\n*Hearts of Summer (2017)\n*Dove Pilot (2015)\n\n==Charts==\n{|class=\"wikitable\"\n!Song\n!Chart\n!Peak<br>position\n!Date\n|-\n|alight=\"center\"|\"The Light\"\n|align=\"left\"|[[Lista Przeboj\u00f3w Programu Trzeciego|Polish Singles Chart]]<ref name=\"polskieradio.pl\"/>\n|align=\"center\"|11\n|align=\"left\"|2 May 2009\n|-\n|alight=\"center\"|\"Can't Get Through\"\n|align=\"left\"|Polish Singles Chart<ref>{{cite web |url=http://lp3.polskieradio.pl/notowania/?numer=1467 |title=Polish Singles Chart |work=[[Lista Przeboj\u00f3w Programu Trzeciego]]}}</ref>\n|align=\"center\"|45\n|align=\"left\"|13 March 2010\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist\n| refs =\n\n<ref name=\"polskieradio.pl\">\n{{cite web\n| url         = http://lp3.pl/alpt.phtml?m=1&nn=1394#navigation\n| title       = Notowanie nr 1422z dnia02.05.2009\n| author      =\n| date        =\n| month       =\n| year  